ABC RETAIL SOLUTIONS
RETAIL DATA ENGINEERING PROJECT
End-to-End Data Processing and Business Intelligence Solution
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

PROJECT OVERVIEW
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Organization: ABC Retail Solutions
Project Name: Retail Sales Data Engineering Pipeline
Objective: Process multi-source retail transaction data into clean, validated
          datasets for business intelligence and decision-making
Scope: Data ingestion, validation, cleaning, transformation, and KPI generation
Timeline: Development and implementation within 2-day sprint

BUSINESS CONTEXT
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

ABC Retail Solutions operates retail businesses across 5 major Indian cities:
• Mumbai (Online + Offline)
• Delhi (Online + Offline)
• Bangalore (Online + Offline)
• Hyderabad (Online + Offline)
• Chennai (Online + Offline)

Current Challenges:
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Multiple data systems produce inconsistent transaction records:
1. System A (retail_data1): 4,243 transactions
2. System B (retail_data2): 4,251 transactions
3. Both systems have overlapping, duplicate records
4. Missing price information in ~5% of records
5. Customer names stored in plain text (PII exposure)
6. Inconsistent date formats across systems
7. No standardized product naming conventions
8. No automated revenue reporting by city/category/payment method

Business Impact:
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Revenue discrepancies between systems
• Inaccurate financial reporting
• Regulatory compliance risks (PII exposure)
• Manual data reconciliation burden
• Unreliable dashboards and KPIs
• Slow decision-making


SOLUTION ARCHITECTURE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

PIPELINE DESIGN
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Input Data (Excel File):
│
├─ Sheet: product_details (10 products)
│  └─ Columns: product_id, product_name, category, price
│
├─ Sheet: retail_data1 (4,243 transactions)
│  └─ Columns: transaction_id, customer_id, customer_name, product_id,
│             price, quantity, transaction_date, city, category,
│             payment_method, discount, email, phone, payment_status
│
└─ Sheet: retail_data2 (4,251 transactions)
   └─ Same structure as retail_data1


PROCESSING PIPELINE
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Stage 1: INGESTION
  Input: 8,494 transaction records (combined from both systems)
  Actions:
    • Load all Excel sheets
    • Validate sheet existence
    • Profile data structure
  Output: DataFrames ready for validation

Stage 2: VALIDATION
  Input: Raw DataFrames
  Actions:
    • Schema validation (required columns present)
    • Primary key validation (transaction_id not null)
    • Data type verification
    • Null profiling by column
    • Duplicate detection
  Output: Quality report, warnings/errors

Stage 3: CLEANING
  Input: 8,494 rows from combined data
  Actions:
    • Impute missing prices (2-tier: product lookup → category median)
    • Remove exact duplicates (all columns identical)
    • Remove transaction-level duplicates (same customer/product/date/qty)
    • Remove invalid quantities (qty ≤ 0)
    • Standardize categorical values (trim, title-case)
    • Parse transaction dates to ISO format
    • Mask PII (customer_name, email, phone) using SHA-256
    • Standardize product names (lowercase, trim, normalize spacing)
  Output: 7,914 cleaned rows (6.8% reduction)

Stage 4: TRANSFORMATION
  Input: 7,914 cleaned rows
  Actions:
    • Join with product dimension table
    • Calculate revenue = (price × qty) - discount
    • Estimate profit = revenue - (cost)
    • Extract time features (year, month, week, day_of_week)
    • Calculate discount rate
    • Create product name standardized column
  Output: Enriched dataset with business metrics

Stage 5: AGGREGATION
  Input: 7,914 enriched rows
  Actions:
    • Calculate global KPIs (total revenue, transactions, profit, etc.)
    • Aggregate by category
    • Aggregate by city
    • Aggregate by payment method
    • Aggregate by payment status
    • Rank top products
  Output: Structured KPI dictionary

Stage 6: EXPORT
  Input: Cleaned dataset + KPIs
  Actions:
    • Export to CSV (for Power BI / Excel)
    • Export to XLSX (Excel format)
    • Export KPIs to JSON
    • Create audit log
  Output: Files ready for BI consumption


DATA QUALITY TRANSFORMATIONS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. MISSING PRICE HANDLING
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Problem: 404-405 null values in price field per dataset

Strategy (2-Tier Approach):
  Tier 1 - Product Dimension Lookup:
    • Create lookup: product_id → standard_price from product_details table
    • Fill null prices using product_id mapping
    • Expected fill rate: ~95%
  
  Tier 2 - Category Median Fallback:
    • For remaining nulls (orphaned products):
    • Calculate category_median = median price per category
    • Fill with category median
    • Ensures 100% coverage

Result: No remaining null prices
Rows Affected: ~400-410 per dataset
Method: Preserves business logic (don't drop transactions)


2. DUPLICATE REMOVAL
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Problem: ~600-700 duplicate records across both systems

Strategy (Multi-Level Deduplication):
  Level 1 - Exact Duplicates:
    • Drop rows where ALL columns are identical
    • Removes obvious errors
  
  Level 2 - Transaction-Level Duplicates:
    • Drop based on key fields: customer_id, product_id, transaction_date,
                                quantity, price
    • Identifies same real-world transaction (different system timestamps)

Result: Clean transaction dataset (no duplicate revenue)
Rows Removed: ~580-623
Impact: 6.8% data reduction (acceptable threshold)


3. VALUE STANDARDIZATION
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Problem: Inconsistent text values across records

Transformations Applied:
  • Category: Trim + Title Case
    Input:  ['ELECTRONICS', ' clothing ', 'home & garden']
    Output: ['Electronics', 'Clothing', 'Home & Garden']
  
  • City: Trim + Title Case
    Input:  ['MUMBAI', 'delhi', 'New delhi']
    Output: ['Mumbai', 'Delhi', 'New Delhi']
  
  • Payment Method: Trim + Title Case
    Input:  ['CREDIT CARD', 'cash', 'DEBIT CARD']
    Output: ['Credit Card', 'Cash', 'Debit Card']
  
  • Payment Status: Trim + Title Case
    Input:  ['successful', 'FAILED', 'pending']
    Output: ['Successful', 'Failed', 'Pending']
  
  • Product Names: Trim whitespace + Normalize spacing
    Input:  ['  Laptop  ', 'sofa_bed-deluxe', 'TV']
    Output: ['Laptop', 'Sofa Bed Deluxe', 'Tv']
  
  • Transaction Date: Parse to ISO 8601 (YYYY-MM-DD)
    Input:  ['01/06/2026', '2026-06-01', '06-01-2026']
    Output: ['2026-06-01', '2026-06-01', '2026-06-01']

Result: Consistent, aggregatable data


4. PII PROTECTION (GDPR Compliance)
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Problem: Customer names, emails, phone numbers exposed in raw data

Approach: Irreversible SHA-256 Salted Hashing
  • Not encryption (cannot decrypt - requirement met)
  • Deterministic (same input always produces same hash)
  • One-way function (cannot reverse)
  
  Implementation:
    hash = SHA-256(original_value + salt)[:16]
    salt = "ABC_Default_Salt" (unique per organization)
  
  Columns Masked:
    • customer_name → customer_name_masked
    • email → email_masked
    • phone → phone_masked
  
  Original columns: Deleted after masking
  
  Benefit: Rows can still be joined (same customer = same hash)
           Data is GDPR-compliant
           No PII in outputs


BUSINESS METRICS CALCULATIONS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

TRANSACTION-LEVEL METRICS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Revenue:
  Formula: (price × quantity) - discount
  Logic: Total sale value after discount
  Validation: Clipped at 0 (no negative revenue)
  
  Example: price=100, qty=2, discount=10
    revenue = (100 × 2) - 10 = 190

Cost Estimate:
  Formula: (price × quantity) × 0.4
  Assumption: 40% of transaction value is cost (60% margin)
  Purpose: High-level profitability assessment
  
  Example: price=100, qty=2
    cost = (100 × 2) × 0.4 = 80

Profit:
  Formula: revenue - cost
  Range: 0 to revenue (by construction)
  
  Example: cost=80, revenue=190
    profit = 190 - 80 = 110

Profit Margin %:
  Formula: (profit / revenue) × 100
  Range: 0-100%
  Use: Identify product profitability


GLOBAL AGGREGATIONS
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Total Revenue: Sum of all transaction revenues
  Purpose: Top-line business metric
  Current: ₹1,501,410,824.60

Total Transactions: Count of unique transaction_ids
  Purpose: Transaction volume metric
  Current: 7,914

Average Order Value (AOV): Total revenue / transaction count
  Formula: ₹1,501,410,824.60 / 7,914
  Current: ₹189,715.80
  Use: Customer spending pattern analysis

Total Profit: Sum of all profits
  Formula: Sum(revenue - cost)
  Current: ₹900,845,784.60 (60% of revenue, as expected)

Total Discount Given: Sum of discount amounts
  Current: ₹1,775.40 (0.12% of revenue)
  Insight: Minimal discounting strategy


