ASSUMPTIONS & DESIGN DECISIONS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. Price Imputation
   Assumption: Product dimension has authoritative prices
   Decision: Use product lookup first, category median as fallback
   Rationale: Preserves transaction records while using best available data

2. Duplicate Handling
   Assumption: Duplicates are system errors, not legitimate re-orders
   Decision: Keep first occurrence, remove others
   Rationale: Same customer, product, date, amount = same transaction

3. Cost Estimate:

   The source dataset does not contain product cost information.

   To enable profitability analysis, category-specific cost assumptions were applied.

   Category Cost Assumptions:

    Electronics      → 80% cost (20% margin)
    Furniture        → 60% cost (40% margin)
    Clothing         → 50% cost (50% margin)
    Home Appliances  → 70% cost (30% margin)

   Formula:

    Cost = Price × Quantity × Category Cost Ratio

    Profit = Revenue − Cost

  These assumptions were used solely for analytical purposes and can be replaced with actual product cost data if available.
4. PII Protection
   Assumption: Can't decrypt customer data after masking (requirement)
   Decision: Irreversible SHA-256 hashing
   Rationale: GDPR-compliant, prevents accidental exposure

5. Row Clipping
   Assumption: Some transactions may have calculation errors
   Decision: Clip profit to minimum 0
   Rationale: Prevents nonsensical negative values

6. Date Parsing
   Assumption: transaction_date may have mixed formats
   Decision: pd.to_datetime with errors='coerce'
   Rationale: Flexible parsing handles multiple formats


